T1  - Higher market valuation of companies with a small board of directors
AU  - Yermack, David
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 40
IS  - 2
SP  - 185
EP  - 211
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/02/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(95)00844-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X95008445
KW  - Boards of directors
KW  - Corporate governance
AB  - I present evidence consistent with theories that small boards of directors are more effective. Using Tobin's Q as an approximation of market valuation, I find an inverse association between board size and firm value in a sample of 452 large U.S. industrial corporations between 1984 and 1991. The result is robust to numerous controls for company size, industry membership, inside stock ownership, growth opportunities, and alternative corporate governance structures. Companies with small boards also exhibit more favorable values for financial ratios, and provide stronger CEO performance incentives from compensation and the threat of dismissal.
